stylometry: Nodes are given points in a transshipment problem.  They can be factories, warehouses, or dealers.  They are places where product can be held in a transshipment problem.  Arcs are the paths between nodes in a transshipment problem.  They show which paths between nodes products can take.  Flows are the quantity of product flowing on the arcs between the nodes.  In transshipment problems, product can flow across multiple arcs and stop at multiple nodes throughout the process.  In transportation models, there is an origin and a destination.  Products can only have one origin and one destination.  A transshipment problem would be encountered by an automaker in determining where cars are manufactured, where they are warehoused, and where they are sold.  These locations are nodes.  The interstate or rail lines are the arcs on which the products travel.  The flows are the quantity of cars shipped over an arc.
